Q22. What is Builder pattern?
Builder Pattern ek Creational Design Pattern hai jo complex object ko step-by-step create karta hai.
In Simple : Constructor se complex object banana mushkil ho, to Builder use karo.

Q23. Why use Builder pattern?
When an object has many optional settings,
to avoid having too many constructors,
and to make creating the object easy to read and use.

❓ Problem Without Builder (Constructor Problem) ?
class User {
    String name;
    int age;
    String email;
    String phone;
    String address;

    public User(String name, int age, String email, String phone, String address) {
        ...
    }
}
❌ Too many constructor parameters
❌ Confusing parameter order
❌ Optional fields hard to manage

1️⃣ Product Class :
class User {
    private String name;
    private int age;
    private String email;
    private String phone;

    private User(Builder builder) {
        this.name = builder.name;
        this.age = builder.age;
        this.email = builder.email;
        this.phone = builder.phone;
    }

    @Override
    public String toString() {
        return name + " " + age + " " + email + " " + phone;
    }


2️⃣ Static Builder Class :
    public static class Builder {
        private String name;
        private int age;
        private String email;
        private String phone;

        public Builder(String name, int age) { // mandatory fields
            this.name = name;
            this.age = age;
        }

        public Builder email(String email) {
            this.email = email;
            return this;
        }

        public Builder phone(String phone) {
            this.phone = phone;
            return this;
        }

        public User build() {
            return new User(this);
        }
    }
}

3️⃣ Client Code :
public class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        User u1 = new User.Builder("Meraz", 25)
                        .email("meraz@gmail.com")
                        .phone("9999999999")
                        .build();

        System.out.println(u1);
    }
}
